	   <tr><td colspan=2><i>I am he who records the workings of the Iksar. I am without name, without brood, without guild affiliation. Know then that I record truth, dispassionate and uncolored. </i><br><br>Section 2:  The Strategist<br><br>In the year of the reign of no king or emperor, in the city of New Sebilis. <br><br>The formative years of the Empress were spent in much the same manner as other members of the Brood of Kotiz.  Early stages of magical development were monitored by the Nihilists, and outside associations were actively discouraged.  During these times, she who would be Empress developed into one of the <b>coldest</b> of the Iksar.  She was calculating, crafty, and had a patience that even the guild of monks admired.  In these early stages, even with the harsh punishment associated with those of the Brood who did try to make personal associations with other members of Iksar society, Usula was unique.  She sought out those members of the monks, shaman, and shadow knight guild to hunt at the foothills outside of Cabilis in the Lake of Ill Omen.  As a member of the Brood of Kotiz, she was not required to go through the testing required by the other guilds within Cabilis.  After all, the test of the Necromancer was survival.  Many died at young ages due to the miscasting of spells or due to the goblin hunters who constantly try to pick off the Iksar young.<br><br>As Usula grew in power, she also formed a group of sorts.  To the leaders of the city, it seemed as if another gang had been formed;  not an uncommon event in such a dangerous land; so they gave it little attention.  This was the folly of the elders.  Usula was uniting the younger members of the Iksar, not based on the general rivalries that the Leaders were supporting (those being the tension between the Shaman and Necromancer classes), but based on the individual ability of those she recruited to her cause.<br><br>Her raids on the Sarnak Fort in the Lake of Ill Omen, which was conducted using two separate groups, each with a warrior, a shadow knight, a shaman, a necromancer, and two monks, became a model for the small combat units the Empire now employs.  Not only did this increase the trust required between the various members, counteracting the ramblings of the guild leaders (who would continue the division within the city), but also built up a formative force that used all the talents of the Iksar.<br><br>And though Harbinger Glosk did not take action, his mind was filled with vague fears.<br><br>--- to be continued<br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Sat Dec 22 21:02:51 2001</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Usula Wurmbane-Infection<br>Iksar Necromancer<br>Empress of Fear</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
