<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100902593556194></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100902593556194><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=2076&mid=100902593556194>Know Thine Enemies, part 3</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=2076&mid=100902593556194#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Scholar>Arjaizen</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>65 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Dec 22nd 7:58 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>(/ooc on) Again, a copy of a post that appears on my page, placed here to aid in story continuity,)<br>(/ooc off)<br><br>The boat approached the shore under cover of darkness, though even in the day, The area surrounding the Toxxulian forest seemed enshrouded in gloom. The canny Iksar monk had no desire to take chances, however. Only a fool would make a landing on the coast of Odus in daylight, if he was of a race the high men considered unwelcome, and Charssk would be most decidely unwelcome here. <br><br>A small river wound through the forest. The raiding party's landing had been in the southern part of the island, as according to his information, the Erudite guards never came to that part of the Forest. His raiding party consisted of six Iksar, three dark knights, a necromancer, and another monk besides himself. He would have preferred less brawn, and more brains, but you made do with what you could. The boat was hidden, and party quickly made its way along the riverbank to where he was told there was a bridge. It was there where he would meet his contact. <br><br>An hour later, they were in sight of the bridge. As best as Charssk could tell, it was close to the appointed time - their contact should be appearing at any time. <br><br>Shortly, they heard a crashing sound, as though a huge boulder was rolling down a hill though dense underbrush. On the breeze, slight though it may have been, was a stench that made Charssk wish the Iksar olfactory glands were a bit less sensitive. Through the trees, he saw the source of the noise and smell. A huge, misshapen troll (weren't they all?) smashed his way through a tangled mass of foliage and sat down on a nearby rock. Scratching his hind quarters, he took out a bottle and drank its contents before unleashing a loud belch. <br><br>Charssk stepped out from the bushes and called out, &quot;Greetingsss, minion of the Emperor. I am Charssk, sent here by Empress Usula herself. Identify yourself, or...&quot; <br><br>&quot;Or WHAT?&quot; The troll bellowed. &quot;You think you scare me, you puny lizard? I'll break you in half and use your bones as a toothpick!&quot; Snorting, then laughing out loud, he continued. &quot;Rungupp. And this is MY forest. So if you want my help, act like it.&quot; <br><br>&quot;Forget your idle threatsss, troll,&quot; Charssk spat. &quot;I am not alone, and you are. Where is the softskin paladin, the Izrhume?&quot; <br><br>&quot;Bah,&quot; Rungupp answered. &quot;The peanut heads all look alike to me. How should I know?&quot; <br><br>&quot;Thiss one carries a sword, and a shield with this ssymbol on it. You have seen it?&quot; <br><br>Rungupp looked over the sketch of the shield pattern. &quot;Yah,&quot; he said, nodding. &quot;I saw him head to Erudin last night from Paineel. He fights the dogs in the Warrens all the time. I was going to jump him, but he had friends.&quot; <br><br>&quot;Ssso do I,&quot; the monk responded. As he made a gesture, the rest of his raiding party appeared through the bushes. &quot;The Empress wishes him brought to her, and she will have him.&quot; <br><br>&quot;Hmph,&quot; the big Troll snorted. He waved a huge hand in the direction of the bridge. &quot;Cross the bridge. Turn right, go straight. You'll get there. Coupla guards in front. Besides them, there's nothing across the bridge worth mentioning.&quot; He got up, scratched himself again, and wandered off towards the south. <br><br>Charssk turned to his party. &quot;Come, we will hide ourselves near to the entrance to Erudin, and capture the ssoftskin when he next leavesss the city.&quot; <br><br>With that, the Iskar raiding party marched across the bridge, and made their way to Erudin. <br><br>--- <br><br>Rungupp snickered to himself as he ran towards the entrance to Paineel. The paladin was wanted by the Iksar queen, was he? Capturing him would be a good way to curry favor with her, and maybe with Emperor Pusbag, as well! If there was going to be glory in capturing this peanut head, it wasn't going to be had by the lizards, that Rungupp would make sure of. <br><br>He hid in some foliage near the Paineel entrance. The Paladin should come out soon, he was sure of it. He sold his loot in Paineel, now that the Heretics there saw the value of his sword in killing the dogs infesting the Warrens under Stonebrunt, but every few days, he still made his way to Erudin with a bag of kobold teeth. <br><br>The Troll shaman grinned broadly, showing a ghastly set of greenish-yellow teeth. He would bring the paladin's head to his king, and maybe then he could get off this Innoruuk forsaken rock for good. he chuckled to himself, imagining feasting on pickled froglok back in Grobb. His wait wouldn't be long. It was almost time... almost time. <br><br>--- <br><br>The troll was going to die, that much was certain, Charssk vowed to himself. &quot;Nothing worth mentioning,&quot; he said. The monk he'd sent ahead as a scout was found in two pieces on the ground by one of the dark knights. The other two were cut down by the Emissary and Sentinel that had been waiting in ambush for them, though the shadow knights had put up a good fight. They managed to summon a pair of pets to help them in the battle, which hurt the Erudites, to be sure. <br><br>When Charssk and the necromancer arrived, he felt sure they would kill the pair with no more losses. But when the two softskins were near death, they laid their hands on themselves and healed themselves completely, curse them! They fought like demons, and both shadowknights fell to their swords. The necromancer was next, the Erudites together dispelling his pet, and somehow, they both knew no fear, as his attempts to instill it in them came to nothing. Still, they were both badly hurt when the last shadowknight joined the battle. <br><br>Swords, shields, fists, feet, tails, and spells flew with abandon, and blood covered the ground all about them. The shadowknight and emissary fell to the ground together, their swords buried in each other's chests. Charssk saw his last companion die and hit the Sentinel in the neck with stiff-clawed fingers, crushing his throat. Barely able to stand himself, Charssk looked about him. His raiding party had been decimated, all because of the treachery of one filthy troll. <br><br>The troll was going to die. With that as his mantra, Charssk carefully mended his wounds. His natural healing powers would do the rest quickly enough. Then it would be time for vengeance. <br><br>--- <br><br>There he was! Saliva ran down his chin as Rungupp anticipated the reward he'd get from the Emperor for bringing him the head of this Erudite. He imagined what the paladin's shiny blue tunic would look like on his wall, his trophy for killing him. After the Erudite had run past, Rungupp stepped out of the brush and began to cast a spell of blindness. <br><br>Bejaizen had exited the tunnel from the city of the Heretics and was heading home. It was almost time to leave for the great convention called by Icewind Novastorm, and he could afford little in the way of delay. As he quickly made his way through the forest, he felt his head start to swim, and his vision begin to go dark. Shaking his head, he managed to throw off the effects of the spell in time to see a troll charging towards him! Swinging his crystallized sword in a wide arc, he sliced a vicious gash in the trolls midsection. Completing the swing, he cast a fast Yaulp spell, and felt a surge of strength course through him. Then, with that strength, he bashed the troll with his shield, interrupting the casting of it's next spell, as well as stunning it briefly. <br><br>In a fit of anger, Rungupp swung a large fist at Bejaizen's head, but Bejaizen ducked it deftly, countering with another deadly slash of his sword. Rungupp suddenly realized, too late, that he had taken on more than he could handle. He tried to run, but Bejaizen smashed him again with his shield, with the same effect. Before he could come to his senses, the paladin removed the troll's head with a final stroke of his sword. <br><br>Bejaizen put the head in an empty bag. He knew there was a reward out for this troll, and the head was the proof he needed that his pest would no longer trouble the forest of Toxxulia. <br><br>He hoped there were no more delays on his trip back to Erudin. He did not want to miss the morning boat to Antonica... <br><br>--- <br>(More to come, including Bejaizen's encounter with Charssk...) <br>---<br><br>Bejaizen, of the Clan Izrhume<br>17th Rank Paladin of Quellious<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Sat Dec 22 08:07:59 2001</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>21st Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Centurion Politico, 7th Legion</td></tr>
