	   <tr><td colspan=2>/OOC<br><br>No doubt that the TLC on the FV server really <i>can</i> put a damper on some aspects of roleplay as some of us have come to view it, but there are arguably some advantages that come with that one major disadvantage.<br><br>The worst disadvantage that I have encountered with it so far is not really that much of a disadvantage at all.  That being that, if you care about getting experience through personally obtaining quest items, you have to put some serious planning into any quests you wish to pursue.<br><br>By that statement, I mean that you may have to run here and there at some point in time, taking out the mobs related to each quest at the point in your development where they are appropriate for your level (i.e. when they still give you experience <i>and</i> drop the quest items).<br><br>The good news is that, in putting in the TLC, they practically eliminated NO DROP.  Only things like newbie notes and epic weapons, according to Verant, are NO DROP.<br><br>Verant's elimination of NO DROP on <i>almost all</i> items means that those things that you need for a quest that TLC prevents you from directly obtaining yourself can, theorectically, be <i>indirectly</i> obtained from another player.<br><br>Maybe they had intended this to force players to widen their circle of associates beyond those at their current level, because I really think it will require us to do so at some point or another.<br><br>Yes, Pusbag needs to get off his butt and upgrade to run Luclin.  Hell, <i><b>I</b></i> need to upgrade to more machine to run Luclin better, too!  The graphics and textures are rich.  Unfortunately, I would also have to be to upgrade to take full advantage of them.<br><br>I am holding off on a decision about deleting my Human Monk, Djian, on the FV server and recreating my Vah Shir Beastlord, Abufazzar, there until I hear something from you all.<br><br>Warric, he of the too many characters and too little time<br>&nbsp;<