	   <tr><td colspan=2>/ooc<br><br>I suggest nothing of the sort.  While Judd Jaggedoak may know who Lashara's father is, he is not telling anyone.  It is certain it is not Judd himself.  As for Judd's overtures to Lashara, he is far to humble and shy to make any approach to her (besides being on the wrong server).  He may not be too old in elf years, I guess.  I actually was just trying to distance myself from the possibility for now.  You know how guys are about the &quot;m&quot; word.  I can assure you this, I plot no surprises.  I think that Judd will dissapear into the wilderness of Norrath and Luclin very soon and it will be impossible for anyone to find him until he wants to be found.<br><br>Why must it be revealed whom Lashara's father is?  I think once you settle upon a famous wood elf that you like, you will choose him.  Or you will simply leave it alone and evryone can speculate forever or let the mystery fade.  I will not write about it at all.  I simply gave you the bait for a story of another time.  It is the same as when Pusbag gave me the troll Braag to write about.<br><br>Alas, take no offence, please, to anything I have written.  I leave it to you to decide which way your character goes.  As for Pusbag's assumption of a wedding, it seemed to me he had expected one between us.  I, personally, envision Judd Jaggedoak as an eternal loner.  Maybe one day some elven maiden will slow him down.  I know there is plenty of room for Lashara to develop however she sees fit.<br><br>During the battle in the swamp, niether Judd nor Lashara participated.  They were missing fingers after all and I didnt know how I wanted to approach such a dilemna, so they simply escaped.  I am sure that Lashara, being a ranger, is a formidable warrior.  I hope that you would post more about her history or simply her activities.  I see that Icewind restored her fingers, as I thought might happen anyway.<br><br>As for evryone else, it is probably time to hurl taunts at each other again for awhile.  I look forward to hearing about all your activities.  I also await, with great anticipation, the story of Sir Parttime's dwarven paladin. <br><br>Once again, I meant no jokes about the identity or history of Lashara.  I think if you read back through all the posts, I really did not write too much about her at all.  Perhaps Judd Jaggedoak is just another of the smitten wood elves who have had the occasion to meet Lashara.  Please enlighten us all about her.<br><br>p.s. - others reading these posts must shake their heads and wonder about our sanity.  I don't care, I love roleplaying and I am having a ball of fun. <br>&nbsp;<br>Judd Jaggedoak <br>Wood Elf Ranger<br>Master Fletcher<br>Torvonnilous Server<br><br><br></td></tr>
